# RAG Engineering Rules

These rules apply specifically to the AI/ML side of the system: retrieval logic, prompt construction, embedding pipelines, and evaluation. Quality issues here are subtle and rarely caught by traditional tests — special discipline is required.

## The cardinal rule: separate retrieval from generation

**Never** write a single function that goes from question to answer. Always:

1. A retriever that takes a question and returns chunks.
2. A prompt builder that takes chunks and a question and returns a prompt.
3. A generator that takes a prompt and returns an answer.

This separation is testable, debuggable, and lets you swap any layer independently. Bundling them is the single most common source of AI engineering pain.

## Embedding consistency

- **Pin the embedding model in config.** Never let it be implicit.
- **Embedding model used at retrieval MUST equal embedding model used at ingestion.** Any mismatch silently destroys retrieval quality. Add a startup check that compares the configured model to the model name stored in Qdrant collection metadata.
- **Document that re-embedding is required for model changes.** A `# WARNING:` comment near the model config is appropriate.
- **Embed text identically at ingestion and query time.** Same preprocessing, same prefixes (some models like BGE require prefixes). If you use BGE, document the prefix in code:

```python
# LEARNING: BGE models require a prefix for asymmetric retrieval.
# The query gets a different prefix than the document. See the model card.
QUERY_PREFIX = "Represent this sentence for searching relevant passages: "
```

## Chunking

- **Chunk size and overlap are configured, not hard-coded.** Default: 500 tokens, 50 overlap.
- **Chunks have deterministic IDs.** Format: `{source_type}_{source_id}_{chunk_field}_{chunk_index}`.
  Example: `tmdb_438631_overview_0`.
- **Idempotent upserts.** Re-chunking the same source produces identical chunk IDs, so re-running ingestion is a no-op for unchanged data.
- **Track the source.** Every chunk's metadata includes: `movie_id` or `person_id`, `source` (e.g., `tmdb_overview`, `wiki_biography`), and `chunk_index`. These are used for filtering and citation.
- **Document-aware chunking is preferred** when the source has structure. A movie's overview is one chunk by default. A long biography is split by section. Configure chunking strategy per source type.

## Prompt construction

- **Prompts are built by pure functions** (no side effects, deterministic output for given input). This makes them snapshot-testable.
- **System prompts live in `prompts/` directory as `.txt` or `.md` files**, not embedded as Python strings. Easier to diff, version, and review.
- **Always include the "answer only from context" instruction** for RAG prompts:

```
You are a movie expert. Answer the user's question using only the provided
context. If the context does not contain the answer, say "I don't have
enough information to answer that." Do not invent facts.
```

- **Include citations in the format you want them returned.** If you want the model to cite chunks by ID, show it the format in the prompt. Don't expect it to invent a citation format.
- **Token budget management.** Compute the prompt length before sending; if context is too large, drop lowest-relevance chunks first. Don't blindly truncate — log a warning and prefer fewer chunks of the right material.

## Generation

- **Use the cheapest model that meets quality bar.** Default: Claude Haiku 4.5. Switch to Sonnet only if the eval set demands it.
- **Set `temperature=0` for factual Q&A.** Higher temperature is for creative tasks.
- **Set `max_tokens` explicitly.** Default 1024 for answers; raise only if eval set has long-form questions.
- **Always pass a `system` message** with the role + instructions. User messages contain only the user's question + retrieved context.
- **Stream responses** for user-facing chat. Buffer for ingestion-time use cases.
- **Implement retries with exponential backoff** for rate limits and transient errors. Use `tenacity`. Do NOT retry on validation errors or 4xx responses.
- **Track tokens and cost per request.** Log them at INFO. Aggregate by user/conversation/feature in metrics.

## Citations

Citations are not optional. Every answer must be traceable to its sources.

- **Return chunk IDs and snippets, not just chunk IDs.** The frontend renders snippets so users see what informed the answer.
- **Cite at the answer level, not in-line.** The LLM can use `[1]` markers if you want, but the citations array attached to the response is the canonical record.
- **Verify citations exist.** If the LLM mentions chunks not in the retrieved set (rare but happens), strip them. Log a warning.

## Evaluation

This is the most under-invested area in RAG projects. Take it seriously from day one.

- **Maintain `eval/golden.jsonl`** with question/expected-answer/expected-citations triples.
- **Start with 10 examples in Phase 1.** Grow to 50-100 by Phase 8.
- **Categories to cover:** factual lookup, recommendation, comparison, "I don't know" cases, edge cases (typos, ambiguous references, very recent movies).
- **Evaluation runner outputs a score report** with per-question pass/fail and an overall score.
- **Run evals on every change to retrieval, prompts, or model config.** Add `make eval` and run it in CI for relevant PRs.
- **Use LLM-as-judge cautiously.** It is biased toward verbose answers. Combine with manual review for tricky cases.

## Caching

- **Cache LLM responses keyed on the full prompt hash during development.** Saves money and time. Use `diskcache` or Redis.
- **Production cache should key on `(question_normalized, top_k_chunk_ids)`** — same retrieval + same question = same cached answer.
- **Cache TTL is short** (24h). The catalog updates; old answers become stale.
- **Never cache personalized prompts.** If the prompt includes user-specific context, do not cache.

## Observability for RAG

- **Use Langfuse (self-hosted) for LLM tracing.** Every request: prompt, retrieved chunks, response, latency, cost, model. This is invaluable when answers are bad.
- **Log retrieval results explicitly.** "Question X retrieved chunks [a, b, c, d, e] with scores [0.91, 0.87, 0.84, 0.81, 0.77]." When a question fails, this tells you whether retrieval failed (no relevant chunks) or generation failed (good chunks, bad answer).
- **Track these metrics:**
  - Embedding latency (p50, p95)
  - Vector search latency
  - LLM latency
  - End-to-end answer latency
  - Tokens per request
  - Cost per request
  - Retrieval recall (when running eval)
  - Answer quality score (when running eval)

## Common failure modes — recognize and fix

| Symptom | Likely cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| LLM invents facts | "Answer only from context" missing or weak | Strengthen system prompt; add explicit refusal example |
| LLM refuses despite good context | Over-strict refusal prompt | Adjust prompt; show example of when to answer |
| Retrieval misses obvious matches | Chunk too big (averaged meaning) | Smaller chunks, or document-aware chunking |
| Retrieval returns wrong domain | No metadata filtering | Add filter by `movie_id` / `source` based on intent |
| Answer is correct but citations are wrong | LLM citing what it "knows" not what it was given | Constrain citation format; verify post-hoc |
| Answers vary day to day | `temperature > 0`, or model auto-updated | Set `temperature=0`; pin model version |
| Embeddings retrieve nothing useful | Embedding model mismatch ingestion vs query | Check model names match exactly |
| New movies don't appear in answers | Ingestion not re-running, or cache stale | Verify scheduler firing; clear answer cache |

## What NOT to do

- **Do not use LangChain agents or chains** for the core RAG loop. Write the loop yourself. The transparency is the point of this project.
- **Do not use `temperature > 0` for factual Q&A.** Reproducibility matters.
- **Do not build retrieval on top of full-text search alone** for semantic questions. Embeddings exist for a reason.
- **Do not embed content that won't be searched.** Wasted compute and storage. If a field is never queried semantically, store it in Postgres.
- **Do not concatenate all retrieved chunks into one giant prompt without thought.** Order matters (most relevant last works well for some models). Token budget matters. Format matters.
- **Do not optimize before measuring.** Get a baseline. Measure with the eval set. Then improve.
